00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:38.860
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: After I was going
to ask you, you always read in bios

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:40.160
and learn about what they did.

00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:41.740
What is an organ scholar?

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:43.040
At Cambridge, you were ...

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:45.290
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: So every,
the whole collegiate system

00:05:45.290 --> 00:05:46.790
in Cambridge, is it
the same at Harvard?

00:05:46.790 --> 00:05:49.570
I don't know what, I don't
know how it works over here.

00:05:49.570 --> 00:05:52.980
But Cambridge University is
made up of different colleges.

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:56.930
So probably the most famous is
King's, King's College Cambridge,

00:05:56.930 --> 00:06:02.030
and then you have Saint John's,
and most colleges have a chapel.

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:05.990
And therefore, a choir
and an organ scholar,

00:06:05.990 --> 00:06:08.520
either an organist choir master

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:10.750
or such it happens
at King's and John's.

00:06:10.750 --> 00:06:14.600
Steven Cleary is the organist and
choir master so he plays the organ.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:20.050
But most of the time he conducts
a choir and has, as his assistant,

00:06:20.050 --> 00:06:24.300 position:56%
or assistants, one or two organ
scholars and it's usually staggered.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:27.720
The course is 3 years, so there
will be an organ scholar in year 1

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:31.450
and then year 3, so it's a
sort of overlapping cycle.

00:06:31.450 --> 00:06:34.000
Some colleges don't
have a music director,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.730
and the organ scholar is appointed

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:38.800
to run the whole music
here in the chapel.

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:41.630
I was at Claire College,
which is next door to King's,

00:06:41.630 --> 00:06:45.380
it was much better, by the way.

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:48.710
No. And we had a music
director, call Tim Brown.

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:52.890
When I went, I had a senior organ
scholar who is in the 3rd year

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:55.360
and I played the organ
for the services,

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:57.100
sometimes I conducted
if Tim was away.

00:06:57.100 --> 00:07:01.120
Either the senior organ scholar or
I would conduct the choir, so it's,

00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:03.360
again, it was just another step

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:06.650
on that whole musical
ladder in training.

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:11.230
And the great thing about Cambridge
particularly, it happens at Oxnard

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:13.920
as well, but I think
more so at Cambridge,

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:18.010
that the student music making
was an exceptionally high level.

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:20.080
The instrumental standard
at Cambridge,

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:24.040
not just the music scholars,
but people studying the sciences

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:28.490
or whatever, the instrumental
level was incredibly high

00:07:28.490 --> 00:07:30.510
and people were just
trying things and putting

00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:32.430
on concerts all over the place.

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:34.330
So you could guarantee
anywhere in Cambridge

00:07:34.330 --> 00:07:36.680
on any given day there'd be 4, 5,

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:39.030
6 different concerts
put on by students.

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:40.350
Usually at a pretty high level.

00:07:40.350 --> 00:07:45.230
So it was a fantastic place to
flex your muscles and try things.

00:07:45.230 --> 00:07:49.190
So by the time I was in my
2nd year I started putting

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:51.010
on baroque concerts.

00:07:51.010 --> 00:07:52.310
Because a certain ...

00:07:52.310 --> 00:07:54.780
I'm sure you all remember
the last time I was here,

00:07:54.780 --> 00:07:57.520
I came with a certain Andrew Manze.

00:07:57.520 --> 00:07:58.900
My great, violinist colleague.

00:07:58.900 --> 00:08:02.000
