00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:52.720
It was really fantastic.

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:54.640
Fantastic time.

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:56.940
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: I saw a comment
he said that he described you

00:08:56.940 --> 00:09:01.590
as a very bendy artist, that's
B E N D Y, because you talked

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:05.870
about the malleability
and flexibility of lines.

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:09.680
In your performances you
work toward this and so on.

00:09:09.680 --> 00:09:12.000
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: I think
that's something I've come more

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.380
and more to believe in, I mean.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:18.240
The 20th century sort of started
by verticalizing everything.

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:20.890
Stravinsky started that.

00:09:20.890 --> 00:09:22.190
You know, you think
of the Rite of Spring,

00:09:22.190 --> 00:09:26.720
everything suddenly having been
that way for hundreds of years,

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:31.600
music started being concerned much
more with rigidity and verticality.

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:33.430
And that reflects itself
in all sorts

00:09:33.430 --> 00:09:36.160
of things to do with performance.

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:40.420 position:56%
The more I read and the more I think
about music and music of the past

00:09:40.420 --> 00:09:44.760
and performance practice,
the more clear to me it is

00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:48.950
that that is something that
is absolutely a modern idea,

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:53.310
a modern concept, of
rigidity and stiffness.

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:55.830
We were looking at all
these wonderful manuscripts

00:09:55.830 --> 00:09:57.580
and things today and you just have

00:09:57.580 --> 00:09:59.930
to compare a beautiful
old manuscript,

00:09:59.930 --> 00:10:03.120
or even an old edition,
to a modern edition.

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:05.950
And there's just no,
there's no comparison.

00:10:05.950 --> 00:10:10.560
The old ones are so beautiful
and they contain so much gesture

00:10:10.560 --> 00:10:13.100
and direction, and just the
way things are written out.

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:16.220
Certainly, in manuscript
sources, that's true.

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:21.910
And as a player of the harpsichord,
which is, and I always say this,

00:10:21.910 --> 00:10:28.270
this is not just for you, it is the
most unmusical thing on the planet.

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:29.570
It does nothing.

00:10:29.570 --> 00:10:36.970 position:56%
It is the ultimate machine that goes
"ping" if you're a Monty Python fan.

00:10:36.970 --> 00:10:38.670
That is literally all it does.

00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:42.770
You have no control
over its dynamic.

00:10:42.770 --> 00:10:45.860
You have a little control
over the attack of the note.

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:48.940
Particularly if you're
playing with quill plectra,

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:50.240
which are a little
bit more flexible,

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:53.420
mostly these days people
use plastic.

00:10:53.420 --> 00:10:56.600
They claim it's more durable.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:10:59.370
That's a debatable point,
but plastic is, of course,

00:10:59.370 --> 00:11:00.770
it's a manmade substance.

00:11:00.770 --> 00:11:03.670
If you can imagine a bit
of the spine of a feather,

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:06.350
there is much more animal
flexibility in that.

00:11:06.350 --> 00:11:08.260
Although it's very little,
and it's very subtle.

00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:13.970
So it really is the machine that
goes "ping" and all you have to ...

00:11:13.970 --> 00:11:16.640
All I can do to try
and make you believe

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:19.730
that it's producing music is,

00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:23.250
the two things I have are
how long I play a note,

00:11:23.250 --> 00:11:25.680
and where I play that note in time.

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:30.720
If I were to play a series of
16th notes the same length,

00:11:30.720 --> 00:11:36.070
absolutely metronomically divided,
it's completely mechanical.

00:11:36.070 --> 00:11:40.650
So the only way to make a
shape is to bend rhythmically

00:11:40.650 --> 00:11:43.460
and how you hold the notes down.

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:47.290
So those are the only two things
you have to make the harpsichord

00:11:47.290 --> 00:11:49.950
into a musical instrument,
so it's a big challenge.

00:11:49.950 --> 00:11:55.840
So, flexibility is a necessity
for playing the harpsichord

00:11:55.840 --> 00:12:00.470
and not making it sound like
the most irritating thing ever.

00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:02.780
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: Spontaneity
too, you talk a lot about that,

00:12:02.780 --> 00:12:06.130 position:56%
and I got a kick out of your comment
that you, reading that you wanted

00:12:06.130 --> 00:12:08.880
to bring back romantic excess.

00:12:08.880 --> 00:12:11.090
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: Well, we
have these labels for music.

00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:13.670
You know, you say that
music is romantic,

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:15.120
you talk about romantic music,

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:18.710
