00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:09.610
You've probably been driving along
listening to some nice Tchaikovsky

00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:12.890
or Rachmaninoff on the radio and
then somebody will cut you up

00:13:12.890 --> 00:13:15.120
and you just, you get very annoyed.

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:18.720
So our emotions change
very, very quickly.

00:13:18.720 --> 00:13:20.270
And baroque music does that,

00:13:20.270 --> 00:13:25.010
it's very much a mirror
of our emotions ...

00:13:25.010 --> 00:13:29.150
So that's why, I mean I love
baroque music, in a way,

00:13:29.150 --> 00:13:30.450
the most, because it's ...

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:32.900
I find it very human in it's ...

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:35.090
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: So
that's something else

00:13:35.090 --> 00:13:37.610
about the further back you
go the dirtier it gets?

00:13:37.610 --> 00:13:38.910
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: Yes.

00:13:38.910 --> 00:13:40.210
Yes.

00:13:40.210 --> 00:13:41.510
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: Can
you explain this a bit?

00:13:41.510 --> 00:13:43.650
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: Yeah,
again, there's a perception

00:13:43.650 --> 00:13:47.520
that we gained romantic excess.

00:13:47.520 --> 00:13:51.010
And you go back to baroque music
and it's slightly squeaky clean,

00:13:51.010 --> 00:13:53.250
and classical music is
a little bit dirtier,

00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:57.820
and romantic music is a little bit
more romantic, and then suddenly,

00:13:57.820 --> 00:13:59.560
it all goes wrong with
Mahler and Schönberg

00:13:59.560 --> 00:14:02.990
and then we start again
with neoclassicism.

00:14:02.990 --> 00:14:07.560
But actually, historically
speaking, if you look at and listen

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:11.720
to old recordings, or look at
old sources for violin fingerings

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:19.160
for instance, the idea that
Porter meant of "sliding around",

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:23.340
is an early 20th century excess,
and it didn't happen before that.

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:25.960
Is absolutely the wrong way around.

00:14:25.960 --> 00:14:30.510
In fact, vibrato comes in and
becomes a sort of normal thing

00:14:30.510 --> 00:14:33.450
in the 20th century, but if you
think about portamento there,

00:14:33.450 --> 00:14:36.060
the idea of sliding
around on a violin

00:14:36.060 --> 00:14:40.610
or which comes from vocal art.

00:14:40.610 --> 00:14:43.860
If you look at fingerings
going backwards,

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:49.540
there is more portamento going
backwards in history than less.

00:14:49.540 --> 00:14:54.020 position:56%
So for instance if you look at, take
a great romantic piece of music,

00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:56.160
Mendelssohn's violin concerto.

00:14:56.160 --> 00:15:02.940
That was premiered by Ferdinand
David and we have both,

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:10.750
the great Joseph Joachim, who was
Brahms' violinist who knew David,

00:15:10.750 --> 00:15:15.750 position:56%
is 10 years younger than Ferdinand
David and also played the Brahms ...

00:15:15.750 --> 00:15:20.370
the Mendelssohnic concerto
very successfully.

00:15:20.370 --> 00:15:24.210
If you compare the fingerings
of both of those two violinists,

00:15:24.210 --> 00:15:29.240
the older violinist, Ferdinand
David, has more portamento in it

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:32.570
than the next generation,
Joseph Joachim.

00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:35.490
And it's the same if
you start looking

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:38.580
at piano recordings,
which we have ...

00:15:38.580 --> 00:15:42.960
Of course we have recordings
of people like Paderewski,

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:46.920
but actually the earliest
recordings we have are piano rolls

00:15:46.920 --> 00:15:51.200
and have a guess at when
the earliest pianist

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:54.910
to be recorded on piano
roll was born.

00:15:54.910 --> 00:15:57.820
Have a guess.

00:15:57.820 --> 00:15:59.820
Sir?

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:01.560
&gt;&gt; AUDIENCE: 1805.

00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:08.690
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: That's a very,
very wild guess, but actually 1824.

00:16:08.690 --> 00:16:11.500
I wish there would be some
from 1805, I really do,

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:12.850
'cause that would be fascinating.

00:16:12.850 --> 00:16:17.420
Carl Reinecke was born in 1824,

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:20.310
which was 3 years before
Beethoven died,

00:16:20.310 --> 00:16:21.950
and he left a lot of piano rolls.

00:16:21.950 --> 00:16:25.250
He was in the middle of recording
a whole set of Mozart sonatas.

00:16:25.250 --> 00:16:29.480
He was very much known for
his Mozart performances.

00:16:29.480 --> 00:16:35.490
And he left some pretty wild
and wacky recordings of Mozart.

00:16:35.490 --> 00:16:38.880
And again, if you take
someone like Carl Reinecke,

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:42.470
and the next generation,
Leschetitzky,

00:16:42.470 --> 00:16:50.750
who was Schnabel's teacher, who
was born 6 years later in 1830.

00:16:50.750 --> 00:16:55.650
They both made piano
rolls of Mozart's big,

00:16:55.650 --> 00:16:57.550
great fantasy in C minor.

00:16:57.550 --> 00:17:00.530
The one that starts
with the octaves.

00:17:00.530 --> 00:17:08.810 position:56%
Pianist theater these days would not
dare to break any of those octaves.

00:17:08.810 --> 00:17:14.200
Your teacher would send you out of
the room if you break any of those.

00:17:14.200 --> 00:17:16.870
[inaudible] break those octaves,
you have to find fingerings

00:17:16.870 --> 00:17:19.460
and contortions which will
make it absolutely together,

00:17:19.460 --> 00:17:22.140
and you must play it
rigidly in tempo.

00:17:22.140 --> 00:17:25.330 position:56%
You compare the two recordings of,
the piano rolls of both Leschetitzky

00:17:25.330 --> 00:17:31.500
and Reinecke, out of the 7,
8 octaves at the beginning.

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:36.520
I think Leschetitzky
breaks 5 of them.

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:40.150
Reinecke breaks all but 1 of them.

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:47.510
And he was known as a very
conservative performer of music.

00:17:47.510 --> 00:17:50.490
So the more I look
into this stuff ...

00:17:50.490 --> 00:17:52.000
There's a fantastic book
if you're interested

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.270
by Neal Peres Da Costa who's
a great friend of mine,

00:17:55.270 --> 00:17:56.960
he's in Australia at Sydney.

00:17:56.960 --> 00:17:59.880
He's done lots of research
into this.

00:17:59.880 --> 00:18:03.330
The book is called "Off the
Record" and he looks at all ...

00:18:03.330 --> 00:18:07.730 position:56%
Very, very dispassionately takes all
this, these bits of information ...

00:18:07.730 --> 00:18:11.550
So again, the trend
going backwards is

00:18:11.550 --> 00:18:15.210
for more color, for
more expressivity.

00:18:15.210 --> 00:18:21.510 position:56%
If we listen to that today, teachers
would just walk out of the room.

00:18:21.510 --> 00:18:22.810
Who's right?

00:18:22.810 --> 00:18:24.120
It's an interesting question.

00:18:24.120 --> 00:18:25.420
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: And
what about rubato?

00:18:25.420 --> 00:18:28.470
We were talking a little
bit about this earlier too.

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:32.020 position:56%
And especially since it's not
really notated in these early scores

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:33.350
like the ones we were looking at.

00:18:33.350 --> 00:18:36.330
How do you develop your
sense of when to do these?

00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:38.800
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: It's
by looking at the music

00:18:38.800 --> 00:18:40.100
and just sort of trying ...

00:18:40.100 --> 00:18:41.400
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: Instinct.

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:42.700
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: Well, it's
instinct, but it's also ...

00:18:42.700 --> 00:18:45.190
The thing about rubato is
it is, again if you ...

00:18:45.190 --> 00:18:49.260
Taking an example of earlier
recordings, it's very deliberate,

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:54.170
very very deliberate use
of structural rubato.

00:18:54.170 --> 00:18:58.100
And the thing that is, that
people generally mean these days

00:18:58.100 --> 00:19:02.290
by "rubato" is usually getting
slower, or playing late.

00:19:02.290 --> 00:19:06.000
If you listen to pianists
"doing rubato" in Chopin,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.610
everything is wobbling
all over the place,

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:10.820
but they're playing hands together.

00:19:10.820 --> 00:19:14.550
If you take Chopin knocked onto
something with a very expressive,

00:19:14.550 --> 00:19:18.090
sort of cantabile right hand.

00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:23.520 position:56%
The rubato of a modern player is the
hands are very much linked together,

00:19:23.520 --> 00:19:26.110
and they will do a
little bit of backwards,

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.280
usually backwards rather
than forwards.

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:31.010
But if you listen,
again, to old pianists,

00:19:31.010 --> 00:19:34.960
and they do much more what
both Chopin and Mozart describe

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:37.370
as "keeping the left hand ..."

00:19:37.370 --> 00:19:40.530
Usually, the phrase is,
"playing in strict tempo",

00:19:40.530 --> 00:19:45.230
whereas the right hand
goes around the left hand.

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:50.270
Now, again, if you read Neal's
book, what a 17th, 18th,

00:19:50.270 --> 00:19:53.530
and 19th century musician
meant by "playing

00:19:53.530 --> 00:19:57.930
in strict tempo" is not what
we mean as post-Stravinskyian,

00:19:57.930 --> 00:20:00.880
post-modern musicians as
playing in strict tempo,

00:20:00.880 --> 00:20:02.610
which means basically metronomic.

00:20:02.610 --> 00:20:05.870
So it's a fascinating area of
study, and I think this kind

00:20:05.870 --> 00:20:08.680
of thing is coming
much more into the area

00:20:08.680 --> 00:20:12.130
of performance practice these days.

00:20:12.130 --> 00:20:13.430
Which is great.

00:20:13.430 --> 00:20:19.150
The more I read and try and find
out about this stuff, the more ...

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:23.360
in a way, the more permission it
seems to give me to be expressive,

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:25.990
and to push the boundaries
of expressivity.

00:20:25.990 --> 00:20:30.860
Because, again, I don't find
Monteverdi any less passionate

00:20:30.860 --> 00:20:32.500
or expressive than Rachmaninoff.

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:36.010
It's just a different style of
music and there are different ways

00:20:36.010 --> 00:20:39.180
of creating that expressivity.

00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:42.260
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: So we have this
quintessentially English program

00:20:42.260 --> 00:20:43.890
that maybe you could talk
a little bit about some

00:20:43.890 --> 00:20:45.190
of the pieces on the program ...

00:20:45.190 --> 00:20:46.490
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: Yeah.

00:20:46.490 --> 00:20:47.790
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: And the
Fitzwilliam Virginal Book.

00:20:47.790 --> 00:20:49.090
How that came into being.

00:20:49.090 --> 00:20:50.390
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: It's very big.

00:20:50.390 --> 00:20:56.960
It was collected by Tregian and
it's a massive, massive compendium

00:20:56.960 --> 00:21:00.090
of very, very many composers.

00:21:00.090 --> 00:21:02.950
A substantial amount of
William Byrd, who's perhaps one

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:06.720
of the great, great keyboard
players and composers

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:12.180
of the 16th and early 17th century.

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:14.240
Lots of Doctor John Bull, which is,

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:16.710
I don't know whether you
know John Bull's music,

00:21:16.710 --> 00:21:18.540
it's a little bit strange.

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:21.250
I'm not sure if I'm a great
fan of Doctor John Bull,

00:21:21.250 --> 00:21:23.710
but everybody in the 16th and
17th century seemed to be,

00:21:23.710 --> 00:21:27.980
and he has an incredibly
difficult music

00:21:27.980 --> 00:21:30.460
in the Fitzwilliam Virginal Book.

00:21:30.460 --> 00:21:33.100
One of the sad things about today,

00:21:33.100 --> 00:21:36.850
I've just been seeing all
these wonderful first-editions

00:21:36.850 --> 00:21:39.520
and manuscripts that you
have here and I've been

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:42.640
like a schoolboy in
a candy shop today.

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:44.670
It's been absolutely wonderful.

00:21:44.670 --> 00:21:51.100
There is still not
available a decent edition

00:21:51.100 --> 00:21:54.170
of the Fitzwilliam Virginal Book,
though the one that was published

00:21:54.170 --> 00:22:00.380
at the turn of the 20th century,
the 1902, 1903, is full of errors

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:02.760
and there's been nothing since.

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:06.700
You cannot buy a facsimile,
there's no facsimile online.

00:22:06.700 --> 00:22:09.460
So please, if anybody can do
anything about that, I'd be very,

00:22:09.460 --> 00:22:11.720
very grateful, 'cause
it contains some

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:15.060
of the most incredible
music from that period.

00:22:15.060 --> 00:22:17.940
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: Would this music
have been for small gatherings

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:20.330
at the court or just
private invitation?

00:22:20.330 --> 00:22:21.830
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: The
different things, I mean,

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:25.060
they're different types
of music in the book.

00:22:25.060 --> 00:22:28.310
There are sets of variations
on pop tunes,

00:22:28.310 --> 00:22:31.760
there are fantasies,
there are organ pieces.

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:35.960
There's a whole variety, it's a
real compendium of what was going

00:22:35.960 --> 00:22:37.870
on with the keyboard at that time

00:22:37.870 --> 00:22:41.350
and not particularly designed
for any one instrument.

00:22:41.350 --> 00:22:44.800
That's another thing that
people try and figure

00:22:44.800 --> 00:22:46.750
out which pieces were
played on which.

00:22:46.750 --> 00:22:50.560
Now there are obviously some
of the pieces which are sacred

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:54.580
in nature are more at home on an
organ, but it doesn't mean to say

00:22:54.580 --> 00:22:57.500
that you can't play them on
a harpsichord or a spinet

00:22:57.500 --> 00:23:00.030
or any other instrument
that was around at the time.

00:23:00.030 --> 00:23:02.960 position:56%
And that's true, really,
throughout the 18th century as well.

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:05.640
People were playing, Mozart was
still playing the harpsichord.

00:23:05.640 --> 00:23:08.650
Beethoven started playing, his
first job was as a harpsichordist.

00:23:08.650 --> 00:23:13.180
So, the harpsichord was gasping
for breath still at the end

00:23:13.180 --> 00:23:16.660
of the 18th century,
but it was still around.

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:18.620
So it was still very much and ...

00:23:18.620 --> 00:23:24.600
A good little fact to know is
even Beethoven's Moonlight sonata,

00:23:24.600 --> 00:23:30.320
when it was first published,
was for piano or harpsichord.

00:23:30.320 --> 00:23:33.660
Now can you imagine the
Moonlight sonata on harpsichord?

00:23:33.660 --> 00:23:35.740
It would sound revolting.

00:23:35.740 --> 00:23:38.790
But, yet, it was still a market.

00:23:38.790 --> 00:23:42.280
It was still a market to sell
to people, to old fuddy duddies

00:23:42.280 --> 00:23:44.010 position:56%
who still had a harpsichord at home,

00:23:44.010 --> 00:23:45.510
and perhaps wanted
to play the music.

00:23:45.510 --> 00:23:50.770 position:56%
So, lots of different keyboards were
around still in the 18th century.

00:23:50.770 --> 00:23:52.350
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: So
the term, "virginal",

00:23:52.350 --> 00:23:54.620
is that a variety of
plucked instruments?

00:23:54.620 --> 00:23:57.040
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: It's
basically a ...

00:23:57.040 --> 00:24:00.140
To be precise, it's
the English version

00:24:00.140 --> 00:24:05.060
of what was known in
Belgium as a musilar.

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:11.340 position:56%
It's sort of like a double briefcase
sized long, oblong instrument

00:24:11.340 --> 00:24:13.690
which is plucked more
or less in the middle.

00:24:13.690 --> 00:24:15.140
And it's a little bit like now,

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:17.760
'cause you drive on
the right, don't you?

00:24:17.760 --> 00:24:19.480
Well, we drive on the left.

00:24:19.480 --> 00:24:22.500
I don't really know this, well we
drive on the right side, actually,

00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:24.820 position:56%
but never mind, won't get into that.

00:24:24.820 --> 00:24:28.090
But we have the same thing
with the virginals from Belgium

00:24:28.090 --> 00:24:31.790
and from England, they
just had the keyboards

00:24:31.790 --> 00:24:34.260
on slightly different
sides of the middle.

00:24:34.260 --> 00:24:41.460
But it's a very particular
kind of quite tubular sound.

00:24:41.460 --> 00:24:46.670
It's very pleasant
for about 5 minutes.

00:24:46.670 --> 00:24:48.580
But then it's a little,
I find it a little,

00:24:48.580 --> 00:24:54.630
it just sort of does one
thing, and the sound shape

00:24:54.630 --> 00:24:58.570
of the note decays quite, even
more than the harpsichord.

00:24:58.570 --> 00:25:02.920 position:56%
It's a little sort of drier and more
tubular than the harpsichord even.

00:25:02.920 --> 00:25:10.220
And the action is not as
reliable as a harpsichord

00:25:10.220 --> 00:25:12.150
because of the nature
of where the ...

00:25:12.150 --> 00:25:14.790
It's being plucked more in the
middle and that causes all sorts

00:25:14.790 --> 00:25:16.470
of trouble with regulation.

00:25:16.470 --> 00:25:20.440
There are many, many sources
from the time, the late 16th

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:23.870
and 17th century, that say
that the action was really bad

00:25:23.870 --> 00:25:27.200
and it made it sound like
little pigs grunting.

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:32.420
So I think the virginals, it
was certainly an instrument

00:25:32.420 --> 00:25:35.710
which people had, but I think the
professionals would probably be

00:25:35.710 --> 00:25:37.010
playing on a ...

00:25:37.010 --> 00:25:38.660
On some kind of harpsichord.

00:25:38.660 --> 00:25:39.970
It's a very attractive sound.

00:25:39.970 --> 00:25:41.650
But not for too long.

00:25:41.650 --> 00:25:46.530
