and it was just mind
blowing, really.

00:25:51.700 --> 00:25:55.220
But how did he get to be an
honorary Englishman in this volume?

00:25:55.220 --> 00:25:56.770
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: I
find, I don't know,

00:25:56.770 --> 00:25:58.070
there's something about Sweelinck.

00:25:58.070 --> 00:26:04.000
I mean I've lived in Amsterdam
for 27 years coming on now

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.140
and the Dutch are very, are there
any Dutch people here today?

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:11.520
The Dutch are very,
very interesting people

00:26:11.520 --> 00:26:15.070
and they quite rightly
regard Sweelinck

00:26:15.070 --> 00:26:19.280
as a great Dutch master, as he was.

00:26:19.280 --> 00:26:26.210
But they tend to play him in a
terribly, terribly sort of somber,

00:26:26.210 --> 00:26:32.320
sober, strict, sort
of Calvinist way.

00:26:32.320 --> 00:26:34.930
And I don't think that's
the music at all.

00:26:34.930 --> 00:26:39.150
It's an incredible, and
partly my take on it as well,

00:26:39.150 --> 00:26:41.950
but when you figure
out where he worked.

00:26:41.950 --> 00:26:45.050
He worked at the Old
Church in Amsterdam.

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:46.450
Have you ever been to
Amsterdam, any of you?

00:26:46.450 --> 00:26:50.510
Do you know what happens
around the Old Church?

00:26:50.510 --> 00:26:53.330
It's a rather red colored area.

