00:41:00.540 --> 00:41:04.000
&gt;&gt; AUDIENCE: So I have another
question about ornamentation,

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:07.390
personal expression of
the performer, phrasing.

00:41:07.390 --> 00:41:11.230
Could you speak a little bit more
about your approach verses others?

00:41:11.230 --> 00:41:16.020
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: Well I think
we talked about this earlier.

00:41:16.020 --> 00:41:17.980
Take Bach as an example.

00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:20.780
There's certainly quite
a lot of people,

00:41:20.780 --> 00:41:29.540
even in the historical world, who
frown on you if you ornament Bach.

00:41:29.540 --> 00:41:32.190
You know, cause Bach is, it's
all written down, you don't need

00:41:32.190 --> 00:41:34.150
to do anymore, it's all perfect ...

00:41:34.150 --> 00:41:38.670
Now, that is patently, for me at
least, my understanding of some,

00:41:38.670 --> 00:41:41.830
that's just, that wouldn't happen.

00:41:41.830 --> 00:41:43.810
If you look at all different
sources, if you're looking

00:41:43.810 --> 00:41:48.370
at the French Swedes for instance,
today, there's no manuscript

00:41:48.370 --> 00:41:54.830
from Bach himself, but they're
all copies made by pupils or sons

00:41:54.830 --> 00:41:59.080
and all of these secondary
sources have variance.

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:01.900
Different ornaments,
different slurs.

00:42:01.900 --> 00:42:04.870 position:56%
Now, that's a musicologist's
nightmare, 'cause it means they have

00:42:04.870 --> 00:42:09.190 position:56%
to write pages and pages of critical
commentary trying to figure out

00:42:09.190 --> 00:42:12.820
and make the decisions of which
one they take into an edition.

00:42:12.820 --> 00:42:20.050
For me, it's another example of the
performer has a certain freedom,

00:42:20.050 --> 00:42:22.780
responsibility of freedom,
given a text.

00:42:22.780 --> 00:42:25.480
So, and even Bach.

00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:28.970
Bach was an inveterate tinkerer
looking at the something

00:42:28.970 --> 00:42:30.670
like the Matthew Passion.

00:42:30.670 --> 00:42:33.980
The first verse which I
recorded, is very, very different

00:42:33.980 --> 00:42:36.170
from the version that most
of you have probably heard.

00:42:36.170 --> 00:42:39.540
It's much more decorated,
it's much more ornamented.

00:42:39.540 --> 00:42:42.640
So the idea of adding
stuff was something

00:42:42.640 --> 00:42:45.560
that Bach was doing
for himself anyway.

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:50.850 position:56%
And any performer at that time would
naturally put their take on it,

00:42:50.850 --> 00:42:56.100
it's like any great jazz saxophone
player playing a standard will have

00:42:56.100 --> 00:42:58.510
their own idea of how
to decorate a melody.

00:42:58.510 --> 00:43:02.160
And any violinist in the
baroque or even actually,

00:43:02.160 --> 00:43:05.280
even the classical period, would
probably make his own decorations

00:43:05.280 --> 00:43:09.310
through reports of opera woodwind
instruments, woodwind players

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:11.390
at the beginning of
the 19th century.

00:43:11.390 --> 00:43:14.290
Being criticized for
still doing ornaments.

00:43:14.290 --> 00:43:19.950
So there's a Dussek sonata, the
great, great sonata by one of my,

00:43:19.950 --> 00:43:22.260
again, another one of
my great, great heroes,

00:43:22.260 --> 00:43:24.090
Dussek is a great composer.

00:43:24.090 --> 00:43:30.450
Beginning of a sonata for the
death of Ferdinand of Prussia.

00:43:30.450 --> 00:43:33.260
Where it just starts with
a left hand bunch of notes,

00:43:33.260 --> 00:43:35.600
and he has to right at the
beginning, just very simple,

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:38.000
low notes in quarter notes.

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:42.710
He had to write in the beginning
of the score, this is 1807,

00:43:42.710 --> 00:43:46.740
senza ornamenti: "don't ornament."

00:43:46.740 --> 00:43:51.880
So the whole practice of
music making was imbued

00:43:51.880 --> 00:43:54.480
with personal ornamentation,

00:43:54.480 --> 00:43:58.290
so to say that you shouldn't
ornament Bach is really,

00:43:58.290 --> 00:44:00.160
I think, nonsense.

00:44:00.160 --> 00:44:04.130
It was just expected in
part of being a performer.

00:44:04.130 --> 00:44:07.410 position:56%
And you wouldn't necessarily do that
if you're doing the B minor mass,

00:44:07.410 --> 00:44:10.020
if you've got something
as complex as that,

00:44:10.020 --> 00:44:12.500
and everybody started doing
their own ornamentation then,

00:44:12.500 --> 00:44:14.780
of course, that's slightly bonkers.

00:44:14.780 --> 00:44:18.510
But certainly, when you're playing
a keyboard piece or something

00:44:18.510 --> 00:44:23.110
where a solo performer is
involved in bringing up a piece

00:44:23.110 --> 00:44:25.120
like that then it would've
been expected

00:44:25.120 --> 00:44:31.280
that you would add your own layer
of stuff on top of the foundation.

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:32.680
So that was a long
answer, wasn't it?

00:44:32.680 --> 00:44:34.240
I'm sorry about that.

00:44:34.240 --> 00:44:38.680
&gt;&gt; AUDIENCE: I had another Bach
question which is what do you feel

00:44:38.680 --> 00:44:42.110
about playing Bach on the
piano verses the harpsichord?

00:44:42.110 --> 00:44:45.690
And do you play him on the piano
as well as the harpsichord,

00:44:45.690 --> 00:44:50.290
and which pieces sort of lend
themselves to which instrument?

00:44:50.290 --> 00:44:53.080 position:56%
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: I think it's sort
of a little bit what I said earlier.

00:44:53.080 --> 00:44:54.410
Bach is great.

00:44:54.410 --> 00:44:56.890
The music for me doesn't change.

00:44:56.890 --> 00:45:00.020
I've played Bach on a synthesizer.

00:45:00.020 --> 00:45:01.560
And it's great fun.

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:05.410
When I play Bach on a modern
piano, the music doesn't change,

00:45:05.410 --> 00:45:08.760
but the tool has changed,
it does different things.

00:45:08.760 --> 00:45:13.840
But I always, if I conduct a
modern orchestra doing old music,

00:45:13.840 --> 00:45:18.440
what I do, and why I'm absolutely
committed to old instruments,

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:24.200
is if you play Bach using an
old harpsichord or an organ,

00:45:24.200 --> 00:45:27.780
it shows you so much about the
color possibilities of the music.

00:45:27.780 --> 00:45:30.910
And I use that knowledge, and I
take it with me when I play it

00:45:30.910 --> 00:45:33.840
on the modern piano or on the
synthesizer or whatever it is.

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:38.730 position:56%
So, I'm certainly not one of those
purist early musicians who say, "Oh,

00:45:38.730 --> 00:45:43.790
you mustn't play Bach on a piano."

00:45:43.790 --> 00:45:45.170
I won't say that.

00:45:45.170 --> 00:45:48.830
Because Bach can sound absolutely
gorgeous on a modern piano

00:45:48.830 --> 00:45:51.920
if you have someone that's
sensitive to the music.

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:53.220
I've heard ...

00:45:53.220 --> 00:45:56.020
So, for instance, I've
heard some really,

00:45:56.020 --> 00:45:59.260
really beautiful performances
of Bach on the modern piano.

00:45:59.260 --> 00:46:01.580
And I've heard some
really hideous performances

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:04.880
of Bach on the harpsichord.

00:46:04.880 --> 00:46:08.130
It's not all about the instruments,
but it's about your understanding

00:46:08.130 --> 00:46:11.840
of music through using the
instruments to tell you something

00:46:11.840 --> 00:46:14.840
about the music that
they were written for.

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:17.300
&gt;&gt; ANNE MCLEAN: Maybe
one more question,

00:46:17.300 --> 00:46:20.790
