00:46:49.010 --> 00:46:50.310
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: You
mean in terms of language,

00:46:50.310 --> 00:46:52.230
or in terms of everything that
had to do with baroque opera?

00:46:52.230 --> 00:46:53.530
I mean ...

00:46:53.530 --> 00:46:56.120
&gt;&gt; AUDIENCE: Well, that they
reorchestrated and translated it.

00:46:56.120 --> 00:46:57.980
&gt;&gt; RICHARD EGARR: That's
a tricky one, because ...

00:46:57.980 --> 00:47:03.230
To go back and take part,
if you were, as an audience,

00:47:03.230 --> 00:47:07.500
were transported back to
an opera house in London,

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:09.240
listening to a Handel opera.

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:11.530
It would be a very, very
different experience

00:47:11.530 --> 00:47:14.240
from sitting in an opera house now.

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:17.020
Because you wouldn't be
expected to sit there

00:47:17.020 --> 00:47:20.380
for 5 hours, concentrating.

00:47:20.380 --> 00:47:23.440
You could be doing all
sorts of things in the boxes

00:47:23.440 --> 00:47:25.030
at the back, and you know.

00:47:25.030 --> 00:47:26.980
It's just, it's a different
experience.

00:47:26.980 --> 00:47:29.170
So you know, you would
have to go to a...

00:47:29.170 --> 00:47:32.440
If it was a successful opera,
you'd probably go and see it 4

00:47:32.440 --> 00:47:34.760
